Burke County Board of Education has receivied a letter from the Southern Association of Colleges and Schools Council on Accreditation and School
Improvement (SACS CASI). Because of actions of the elected Burke County School Board, our high schools are now at risk of losing their accreditation. This not only impacts students' applications to certain colleges and universities, but it also also negatively impacts our community as a whole.  We need state leadership to investigate and resolve this crisis which threatens the future of our children and our community.
Below are contents of the letter from SACS CASI:
The letter indicates that a complaint was received alleging violations  under AdvancED  and SACS CASI standards, including but not limited to:

* Standard 1 - Vision and Purpose
* Standard 2 - Governance and Leadership
* Standard 6 - Stakeholders Communications and Relationships
* Standard 7 - Commitment to Continuous Improvement

It states that the Complaint and a review of other public information revealed several troublesome incidents including but not limited to the following:

* The Board's lack of control during a November Board meeting where the 
Board was scheduled to have a first reading of a Book Banning policy.  Public recordings appear to indicate that the Board was apparently upset that 38 students signed up  to speak regarding this issue.  Board members reportedly discussed tracing emails  to determine who organized the students and made the statements that after the 3rd  student speaks there would be no need for further comment because no one would have  anything new to add to the discussion.
* The audio of the November meeting appears to include a statement allegedly attributed to Robert Hairfield, where it sounds as if he makes the statement, "To 
shoot to kill if necessary".  This statement appears to be made in reference to the unruly crowd that was present at the meeting.  However, it is unclear as to who
he is addressing the comment to or the full context of the conversation.
 * On April 6, 2009, two Board members requested that a Board member be  frisked during the Board meeting for a weapon.
* Racist emails were sent by Board member Robert Hairfield containing  racist, discriminatory and inflammatory content.
* The termination of the superintendent's contract without allowing for  public comment and apparently in contradiction to the recommendation of the Board's 
attornery.
The letter continues on to require a response within thirty days of the  letter. The letter is dated April 24, 2009.  That response will then be carefully reviewed by SACS CACI to determine if further action is warranted.  The letter is  signed by Donna James, Ed.D, State Director.
More information on this crisis can be found at <http://www.morganton.com/>www.morganton.com
