Dear Sirs & Madams:

Most of the letters you most likely will receive on this subject are from concerned parents with children in the Burke County Public School System.  My perspective on the matter is not that of a concerned parent of a student, but that of a concerned voter worried about the future of our county. 

In 1995, I moved from Robeson County, my place of birth, to Burke County with my family.  I came from an eighth grade class of about sixty (60) students at Faigrove Middle, into a class of about five hundred (500) at Freedom High School.  In addition to having to make the adjustment to the physical environment, the standards of learning were also much higher in Burke County than those of Robeson County.  It took very little effort for me to excel in my studies as a student in Robeson County.  It was simply not challenging enough in the time that I was there.  When I arrived as a Freshman to Freedom High School, where David Burleson served as principal, not only did I not know anyone there, but I had to work twice as hard to maintain the grades I had become accustomed to achieving.  I welcomed the challenge, but I would argue that this change was overwhelming facilitated by the discipline, pride and confidence exuded by Mr. Burleson through his leadership as principal at Freedom.

In my four years at Freedom, I achieved Academic Excellence, excelled in sports and, ultimately, received an academic scholarship to Lees-McRae College, where I graduated in 2003 with a Bachelor's in Criminal Justice.  This scenario would not be possible for a Burke County student if certain members of the Board of Education are allowed to continue on with their antics. 

Taking accreditation away from the schools is not the answer to clean up the current situation in Burke County.  Doing so will only punish the students.  The students have done nothing to deserve this and cannot speak for themselves.  Therefore, it is up to us as the voters in this county to do what our elected board members will not and protect the futures of the students. 

I ask of each of you, to look deeply into this situation and take into consideration the voices of your constituents.  Break the vicious cycle of the rogue members of this board.  Punish the members who created this and the many other problems in the past:  Tracy Norman, Tim Buff, Karen Sain and Rob Hairfield.  Their decisions are the reason our school's accreditation has come into question and are a result of their personal agendas/vendettas and are not in any way in line with the views and opinions of the people of Burke County.  We, as a County, have attempted to voice our opinions to the named officials and have had our First Amendment rights taken away from us on those occasions.

The people of Burke County can and will clean up this mess, but not until November, 2009.  However, action is needed now.  You can intervene and help save the future of our students.  You will not regret intervening.  You will, however, live with regret should you choose not to intervene.  The futures of over 14,000 students are in your hands.  As elected officials, I would advise you not ignore the more than 90,000 voices of Burke County, NC.  Our voices will make a difference in November and we ALL plan to pick and choose carefully during that joyous time.  The voters deserve to have people in positions such as yours and on the Board of Education who will listen and act with honor and dignity.

I'm not begging you and I'm not even asking you.  It is not my place to do either.  I own my vote, no one bought it.  So, I, as do the other voters of Burke County and the State of North Carolina, own a share in what any elected official says or does and I am simply stating what I expect of those I employ in office. 

Sincerely,
Billie Jo Edmondson

